Neither yet, for all this, (loth Luke fight against Josephus. For this last measures the space to the first foundation of Olivet; the other, to that place of Olivet, where our Saviour ascendcd. The first foot of the mount was distant five furlongs from the city3 but Christ, being about to ascend, went up the mountain three furlongs farther.

The mount had its name from the Oliva-trees, however other trees grew in it3 and that, because the number of these perhaps was greater, and the fruit better. Among other trees, two cedars are mentioned, or rather two mon- sters of cedars. ‘⁶ Two 2¹ cedars (they say) were in the mount of Olivet, under one of which were four shops, where all things needful for purifications were sold: out of the other, they fetched, every month, forty seahs” (certain nicasures) “ of pigeons, whence all the women to be purified were sup- plied.''

It is a dream like that story, that, beneath this mountain, all the dead are to be raised. “When the dead shall live again (say theyb), mount Olivet is to be rent in two, and all the dead of Israel shall come out thence; yea, those right- eous persons, who died in captivity, shall be rolled under the earth, and shall come forth under the mount of Olivet.”
